attachments.title: Test All The Things Vs. Break All The Things: Ship.io Explores Two Ideologies | Ship
attachments.text: Is it better to test every scrap of code or iterate fast and break stuff? Testing is important. Critical. But is it critical from day one? Is it better to test every bit of code as you go, or iterate fast and deal with building tests once you’re really up and running? We posed these questions to two startup veterans: Thomas Overton, Director of Technology at VentureBeat; and Kevin Rohling, founder of CiSimple (now known as <http://Ship.io|Ship.io>) and, more currently, co-founder and VP of Product at Emberlight. First of all, they both urged the importance of context: Every company is different and every product will require a unique approach. But, Overton says, there are some universal benefits to integrating testing early as a part of a strong foundation for the company. “It’s all about setting up good habits and clean code in the beginning,” he says. “It’s a lot easier to get developers to start writing unit tests when you have a fresh application or feature.” That’s all well and good, but as
